We hope you’ve been having a great time exploring Arizona with us! We’ve loved reliving the first week from our trip earlier this year, where we explored Phoenix and Tempe with Cole and Charisma (@roll.with.cole), discovering how wheelchair-accessible the Grand Canyon State really is.

And, as promised, today we’re excited to give you a deeper look into Cole and Charisma’s experience in Arizona and what it’s like to travel using a wheelchair.

Watch the full video to learn more and let us know your thoughts in the comments.   @Visit_Arizona #VisitArizona #PassionPassport #ImagineAZ #ad

node.text:
Wherever in the world that you find yourself, color is there — light is there. In our Discover Your Yellow series with @Expedia, we invited you along on a journey fueled by curiosity, creativity, and courage. These elements are essential to our travels, and allow us to connect with the places we go in a deeper, more impassioned way. Whether it’s watching the sunrise from a mountaintop or sharing a laugh with friends on the road, travelers are experts at following the rhythms in life that give us strength. From Japan to Hawaii, Arizona to Barcelona, we heard four inspiring individuals share their stories with us.
__
Are you the writer, photographer, designer, or dreamer? What are you seeking to discover? Where will you find it? Watch them all, let us know, and remember — you’re always writing your story. #ExpediaYellow #PassionPassport

node.text:
From reaching hidden waterfalls by kayak to snorkeling along the island’s shorelines, our partners at @Expedia invited us along on a trip to Kauai, Hawaii, last year, with speaker and author @RuthieLindsey to explore her close relationship with the natural world on a deeper level through an array of new experiences. As a young woman, chronic pain slowly pulled Ruthie away from everything she once held dear: her faith, her family, her body, and her very self. After not being able to travel during seven bed-ridden years, she now embraces every circumstance for what it is with grace and determination to find healing in ways that inspire her.
__
Head to the link in our bio to see how the color yellow seemed to greet her at every step of the way, reminding her to treasure every circumstance in life for what it is—a lesson learned over the years of her life that led to these moments.
__
What does the color yellow mean to you? Let us know in the comments! 💛 #passionpassport #ExpediaYellow

node.title: Expedia Yellow: Discovering Healing in Kauai with Ruthie Lindsey

From the bold colors of the autumn season to the intense colors of temples and shrines, in this episode of “Expedia Yellow: Discover Your Adventure” with @Expedia, we set out to Japan with Photographer @MichaelGeorge last year to explore his close relationship with the magical color. For Michael, growing up in Florida, yellow was the sun. Always present, year-round, beating down on you relentlessly—it gave everything light and also seemed to slowly burn the world away. Today, it means something more to him.
__

node.text:
Designer and photographer Demas Rusli (@demas) was once skeptical about solo travel. Living in Australia and working in an architecture firm, his enthusiasm and curiosity about use of color and space were his main sources of inspiration. He didn’t want to travel just to visit a place, or boast about his destination. Last year, when our partners at @Expedia planned his trip to Barcelona, he discovered that there was another option: inhabiting the places we travel, and having them inhabit us. Even though he went solo, the warm and playful character of Barcelona both intrigued his eye for design and made him feel at home. All in all, it just inspired to keep Demas doing what he was doing, and stay on track — a message we could all use in this moment.
__
In this episode of “Expedia Yellow: Discovering Creativity,” we follow Demas on his solo-trip through Barcelona and learn how the architecture, light, and design helped him discover his creativity.
__
Head to the link in our bio to read more about how the color yellow inspires him to create in our one-on-one interview with Demas. 💛
#ExpediaYellow #Passionpassport

node.title: Expedia Yellow: Discovering Creativity in Barcelona with Demas Rusli

Last year, we rode along with art director Anne McIsaac (@yellowillow) and @Expedia on a road trip through Arizona that inspired us to think about how travelers learn to take life at their own pace — and maintain that pace even in unforeseen circumstances. Chasing the color yellow across the otherworldly western landscapes, Anne’s journey took her on hot air balloon rides and dreamy drives to catch the next sunset or streak of light on the red rocks of the desert. In this episode of “Expedia Yellow: Discovering Courage,” we follow Anne’s footsteps as she traces the story of her journey with Parkinson’s and her very close creative relationship with the color yellow.
__
Head to the link in our bio to read more about Anne and how the color yellow reminds her to seek joy and curiosity at all times. What does the color yellow mean to you? Let us know in the comments! 💛 #ExpediaYellow #PassionPassport

Welcome to another episode of our “Passport to the 🌎” IGTV Series! This week, @seanslobodan takes us to Utah’s Zion National Park through a trailer for his upcoming feature film, “Where Forever Is Now,” a dedication to its beautiful and powerful land.
__
"The country's national parks might be closed right now, but work goes on behind the scenes to preserve their spirit of adventure and prepare them for the next generation of visitors. Whether you are creative who gains inspiration from the natural world or collaboration with others, Utah's Zion National Park is still synonymous with adventure, even at a time when our experiences are so limited. I hope that our new film encourages people to go out and find their own stories, whether you're streaming it from home or watching in the park's museum auditorium. There's a lifetime of things to see in Zion, but this is a reminder to value the quality of experience over quantity. Like any healthy relationship, we have to be willing to give back to nature as much as we take. It starts with a little less self-interest and a little more self-awareness."
__
A version of this film entitled "We The Keepers" will play every 30 minutes at Zion for the next 10-15 years, with a feature-length cut to be released later this year at festivals. Director Sean Slobodan, @seanslobodan, of @lcl.studio says it's what we do now that will determine what the future looks like in places like our National Parks, and that to stream the video to the public during the closures is a way to emphasize that each of us has an impact. "I firmly believe that the only way we're going to create change in the way that we impact our public lands is by connecting with them personally." 🎥@seanslobodan and @lcl.studio #passionpassportvideo #passionpassport
__

Welcome to another episode from our "Passport to the 🌎" IGTV series! This week, filmmaker @bryanhynes_ takes us on a heartfelt journey to Tanzania.
__
"I had the pleasure of leading an expedition team of international high school students from Dubai. We traveled through Tanzania over a two-week trip, where we trekked through the Southern Parre mountains and local villages. We also worked with a local Massai community in Arusha to help build a beautiful empowerment center for women. A visit to the famous Ngorongoro Crater for a safari tour provided us with the opportunity to witness a variety of incredible wildlife. Throughout this experience, I felt a sense of connection to our world and the human spirit. In many ways, the culture shock of living in rural villages with basic resources was both eyeopening and humbling. It allowed me and my team to reflect on what is important in our lives and to appreciate the little things. I also realized that, as humans, we're not so different. No matter where you come from, we all share in commonalities and can celebrate what makes us unique."
__

We're back with another edition of our "Passport to the 🌎" IGTV series! This time around, our friend @matiasderada takes us to the breathtaking Salt Flats of Bolivia.
__
"In February of this year, I had the opportunity to revisit the Salt Flats of Bolivia. It had been four years since my last visit, but the memory of its never-ending reflection left a lasting impression. It's always been my dream to witness sunset or sunrise in this place, so this time around, I decided to camp for two days with my good friends @theboliviantraveler, @jimenasuarezv, and @arturoplataa. The footage that you see in this video encapsulates my two-day experience, which I can only describe as being both awake and dreaming at the same time. With that feeling in mind, it was only fitting to pair it with a song that feels as if someone is talking to you in your sleep and guiding you through this moment. As cheesy as it may sound, this place is magical in every aspect, and I would come back here a million times if I could."
__

From reaching hidden waterfalls by kayak to snorkeling along the island’s shorelines, our partners at @Expedia invited us along on a trip to Kauai, Hawaii with speaker and author @RuthieLindsey to explore her close relationship with the natural world on a deeper level through an array of new experiences. As a young woman, chronic pain slowly pulled Ruthie away from everything she once held dear: her faith, her family, her body, and her very self. After not being able to travel during seven bed-ridden years, she now embraces every circumstance for what it is with grace and determination to find healing in ways that inspire her.

Head to the link in our bio to see how the color yellow seemed to greet her at every step of the way, reminding her to treasure every circumstance in life for what it is, a lesson learned over the years of her life that led to these moments.

What does the color yellow mean to you? Let us know in the comments! 💛 #passionpassport #ExpediaYellow #ExpediaPic

For Sean Slobodan, a Utah-based director and founder of Local. Studio, the outdoors has always inspired and driven him to create immersive videos that transport his viewers. This film showcases all the beauty that the majestic state of California has to offer. It was a passion project with no clients dictating the schedule or vision: “The state is so big and different from top to bottom that I liked the idea of putting something together that went way beyond the Hollywood experience that most people think of. The film was shot throughout three separate trips and took a total of 3-4 weeks of shooting. This project, in particular, provided a kind of freedom in a film that I don’t often get to feel and experience. We had made some plans before each leg of the trip, but overall we just shot what we saw and luckily a lot of it turned out.” Want to see more videos from @lcl.studio, Sean's Utah-based production company? Check out their website and read our article to learn more about their shooting experience across California. Filmmaker Brent Foster has made it a goal to say "yes" to every place he's invited to see, so when he had the chance to explore Rajasthan for a few days after wrapping a commercial shoot, he jumped at it:

Having spent about a year and a half in India, I knew to expect sensory overload. India is the type of place that you need to embrace and accept for what it is. It’s a visual artist’s paradise, but also a great test on any traveler. It’s one of those places where you have to recognize that you have no control over what goes on around you.

This personal project was the result of this exploration and is a reminder of why I got into filmmaking in the first place — to explore. It was so rejuvenating to step away from the constraints I often feel when doing commissioned work and to just open myself up to being there with the camera with no preconceived shots or expectations.

I find that passion projects, regardless of what stage you're at as a filmmaker, are key to keeping you inspired and loving what you do. I hope to always have one on the go and can't recommend it enough to other filmmakers and travelers. I want to challenge people making their first travel video to get out of their comfort zone and get as close to people as you can when filming. It’s easy to sit back with a zoom lens and capture life from afar. Try to immerse yourself in the process, and you may be surprised by the results.

Want to see more of Brent's films? Visit our website to read our interview with him. For more films from around the world, follow our new IGTV series, “Passport to the 🌎." 🎥: @brentfoster 📍India 🇮🇳#passionpassportvideo #passionpassport

📷 @joelcoronado99 📍Guanajuato, Mexico 🇲🇽 "Photography has long inspired me, thanks to the support of my family and the love I have for traveling with them. With each adventure that we take together, my appreciation for them grows even more. During this trip, and those before it, travel has always brought my family closer together. 

When I travel, my purpose is to show the beauty of each corner of every town or city I'm in. From architecture to gastronomy, crafts, and more, I hope people fall in love with these places like I have.

Before taking this photo, I felt like I needed a new experience in Guanajuato, ultimately discovering this viewpoint from the roof of an old home. Here, I had the best views of the town center.

All this to say, traveling during a pandemic has opened my eyes, and I can not leave the issue aside. In many cases, I've witnessed the impact all of this has had on many people. In Guanajuato, it has led to increased poverty as many people rely on trade, commerce, selling food, and crafts to make a living. I hope that things will improve soon as the world slowly begins to reopen.

If you're traveling during these times, please do it safely. But know that these places need your economic support as a visitor, so be sure to shop and support local while there." #passionpassport

📷 @hugohealy 📍Guayaquil, Ecuador 🇪🇨 "It was my first time in Guayaquil and South America as a whole. I was traveling for work and had a project in the Galapagos Islands and Peru, with a short layover in Ecuador.

My hotel was so close to the colorful community featured in the village. The close-knit suburb sits on a small hill with a beautiful chapel situated at the top. I remember heading into the city and being immediately drawn to the village, knowing I had to capture it.

Before heading out, I did some research and spoke to the staff at my hotel as I heard it could be potentially dangerous for tourists. After speaking to a few people, it was clear that I should not visit at night, so I ventured out at sunrise to capture the first light.

It was a 20-minute walk to the top, 400 stairs in total. And, honestly, I felt pretty nervous and vulnerable but comfortable enough to decide to experience this place on my own.

When traveling in general, it's important to keep your wits about you. Crime can happen anywhere — whether it's in your hometown or across the world. And as creators, we know the feeling of wanting to capture a moment, but it's not worth it if you feel it genuinely puts you at risk.

I'm incredibly happy to have captured this moment and to have experienced this place for myself. Overall, I think it was worth it."
__
Have you ever had a similar experience? Let us know in the comments below. #passionpassport

#ImagineAZ 🌵 Part 2 - Tempe: After spending a few days in Phoenix with Cole and Charisma exploring the cities expansive accessible-friendly locations, we headed east to neighboring Tempe for a 24-hour adventure. 

While here, we discovered that Tempe has its own vibe, and there’s a freedom to have whatever kind of experience comes your way. 📖: To Have and to Hold: Honeymoon Hiking New Zealand’s Kepler Track⁠
📝: Alex Tzelnic (@atz840) ⁠
📷: (@helemakai) 📍Fjordland National Park, NZ🇳🇿⁠
__⁠
"The night before the trek I dreamt that a New Zealand Department of Conservation employee asked me, “Who wants to take a hike in the rain on their honeymoon?” Perhaps this is what I had in mind as my wife and I huddled outside the Fjordland National Park Visitor Centre doors at 7:59 AM, waiting for it to open.⁠
⁠
The Kepler is one of New Zealand’s ‘Great Walks’ and it was to be the culminating experience of our two week honeymoon. We chose this track because it was advertised as a 60 kilometer loop above the clouds through limestone bluffs and gleaming fjords. This was entirely accurate, except that we could barely see the bluffs or the fjords, and said clouds were saturated with a seemingly endless amount of water. It proved to be one of the most trying experiences of our young marriage, and for that reason one of the most fulfilling too.⁠”
__ ⁠
Head to the link in our bio to keep reading about Alex and Courtney's Honeymoon adventure through Fjordland National Park. #passionpassport

#ImagineAZ 🌵 Part 1 - Phoenix: In case you missed it, we're incredibly excited to revisit our trip to Arizona over the coming weeks, where we teamed up with six super talented creatives to explore all the great things Arizona has to offer.

Today, we’re reliving our time in Phoenix with Cole and Charisma (@roll.with.cole), where we set out to discover the most wheelchair-accessible city in Arizona and explore a few not-to-be-missed sights that provide easy access for wheelchair users.

The verdict? For accommodating people with physical disabilities, Phoenix passed with flying colors. From transportation and dining to trails and even a one-of-a-kind fitness center, the nation’s fifth-largest city has it all.

“We loved how pretty much everywhere we went had pretty large … accessible spaces,” Cole said. “It’s so nice to have some extra space when we’re using a ramp to get in and out of our accessible vehicle … it was refreshing to see that larger area in Phoenix.”

📷 @pete_ell 📍Dorset, UK 🇬🇧 "The Jurassic Coast entails 160km of the finest coastal scenery offered in the UK, and the varied rock formations tell a 200-million year story of events from the Jurassic period. I remember this crisp winter morning well, clouds of condensation filling the air with every breath as my friend Drew and I ventured to Durdle Door, a sea arch known around the world for its unmistakable beauty.

The coastline boasts a stunning array of coastal scenery, from airy sea cliffs to beautiful sea stacks. In the winter, the sun rises off the coast, illuminating every crack and crevice of the landscape and creating perfect conditions for shooting — which we took full advantage of this morning. Shortly after this moment, I went for a dip as the sea temperature neared 8 degrees. I find cold water to be therapeutic and beneficial for my mind. The feeling that ensues is one of the greater joys in life. You only need to step outside your comfort zone to get there."
__
Would you take a dip in 8-degree water mid-winter? Let us know in the comments. #passionpassport

node.text:
📷 @thehistoriantraveller 📍Piódão, Portgual 🇵🇹 "When I travel to a new place, I always try to choose destinations with a unique historical relevance. This is typical because of my profession as a historian and because I am intrigued by how places change and shape their visual appearance based on their historical influence.
 
I first heard of Piódão while reading a Portugal guide, and I was immediately fascinated by this little hidden village in the middle of the Serra do Açor. It is one of the only 12 villages a part of the Aldeias Históricas de Portugal (Historical Villages of Portugal). They say during the middle ages, it was a popular destination for people and mostly criminals escaping to the mountainous Arganil region because of its secluded location. After experiencing it for myself, it all made sense. On a rainy or foggy day, you can't immediately find the village and have to look well from the other side of the mountain to see it coming out from the fog.

During this trip, my family and I (husband and two sons) arrived in Piódão, only to be greeted by a massive thunderstorm. I remember barely seeing the street. However, I asked my husband to stop for a moment at a nearby viewpoint. I wanted to verify the fog theory. After a few minutes of waiting under the rain, the village slowly appeared from the mountain. It was magical!

We had to wait for a while at the local bar before getting around without getting soaked, but I remember it as one of the best days I had in Portugal. We ended up tasting the local delicacies, meeting with local people, and taking amazing photos. That thunderstorm was the best thing that could have happened to us that day. It made our experience of Piódão very authentic."
__
How do you choose a place to visit? Is it normally based on history, or maybe it's more than that? Let us know in the comments. #passionpassport
